***REMEMBER. People who died with Covid-19, but not as a result of Covid-19 are being added to the death total. So the death numbers are INFLATED. However, even then, the numbers are reassuring.**
***ADDITIONALLY, the number of cases are under reported, since many people with symptoms never got tested. Thus, the death rate would be MUCH LOWER***

If you're aged 0-49, you should not be afraid of dying from Covid-19.
If you're 0-19 you have a 0.04% chance of dying from Covid-19.
If you're 20-29 you have a 0.06% chance of dying from Covid-19.
If you're 30-39 you have a 0.1% chance of dying from Covid-19.
If you're 40-49 you have a 0.5% chance of dying from Covid-19.
If you're 50-59 you have a 1.5% chance of dying from Covid-19 if infected.
If you're aged 60-69, your chances of dying from Covid-19 is 5.6%

Significant risk happens at 80+. Even then, your chances of survival at 80-89 is 72%

Mind you, that at this age group, your risk of dying from the flu increases exponentially as well.

node.text:
Boletim da Semusa atualizou a situação epidemiológica da cidade

Boletim informativo da Secretaria Municipal de Saúde (Semusa), divulgado na tarde desta quarta-feira (19), confirmou quatro novas mortes em decorrência da Covid-19 em Anápolis.

De acordo com a pasta, um dos óbitos aconteceu na segunda-feira (17), referente a um homem de 65 anos, e os outros três aconteceram ontem (18), todos de mulheres, com as seguintes idades: 39, 72 e 79 anos.
Com essa atualização, o município passa a registrar um total de 153 vítimas fatais.
O boletim da Semusa também trouxe a confirmação de 193 novos pacientes nas últimas 24h, sendo 121 mulheres, de cinco a 97 anos, e 72 homens, de 11 a 94 anos.

Com esse acréscimo, Anápolis ultrapassou a marca dos 7 mil contaminados.
Já são 7.052 pessoas que testaram positivo para a doença desde o início da pandemia. Destas, 4.370 cumpriram o período de quarentena e foram liberadas.
Fonte: Portal6

ABOUT THE COVID-19 VIRTUAL VIDEO TIME CAPSULE:
What I love about great cinema like 1917, Schindler’s List, and Dunkirk is it makes history relatable through seeing human stories, not numbers, not facts in a book. Documenting personal stories is the only means we have of showing the future how COVID-19 affected everyone equally. If you are reading this in the future, I hope that everyone sharing their stories has helped you have a greater understanding of the Coronavirus time period. Thank you to everyone kindly submitting videos for my living history journalism project and thank you for everyone who is watching them. Sincerely, Nicole Russin-McFarland, 2020

Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble nutrient that comes in different forms. It plays a significant role in red blood cell and DNA synthesis, as well as proper neurological function. Therefore, vitamin B12 deficiency involves neurological symptoms, anemia, fatigue, poor cognition, weakness, bleeding gums, and tingling of the hands and feet.
Many subclinical problems of inadequate vitamin B12 intake can arise before neurological symptoms do, especially in the elderly, as the intestinal absorption of the vitamin declines with aging. Certain medications, including metformin, omeprazol, may reduce its absorption. Additionally, chronic stress may deplete B12 levels, making it a noteworthy vitamin for people of all ages.
Therefore, one of the best ways to get B12 is through injections, eluding issues with absorption and liver metabolism. That diminishes its concentration.

node.text:
I like to believe I easily adapt to change...

But... as change comes to my routine in the form of my first day of the Fall semester I feel myself stressing out and honestly becoming really annoyed. 2020 has come with so much uncertainty and change to “the norm” that once I had some semblance of a routine it made me feel more comfortable. 

Now that the semester is starting I feel the uncertainty and fear starting to creep back into my life. The “I’m not sure what will happen when we transition to in person”. The “we have to monitor the situation and see where to go from there”. They all scare me and my fragile new routine I had going. It was simple... easy. I liked it. 

However I can’t let it get to me! I have a set routine that I CAN control. My personal development and workouts. I CAN make those things happen. So I will let that bring me the peace and clarity that I needed to hear after a crazy first day of classes. 

How has the pandemic/2020 made you feel? How has it changed your life?

Times are changing, and school is fast approaching! But don’t worry! We’re here to help! ???

Here are some tips to help you and your young ones learn and adjust during these hard times: 

1. Have a discussion with your family?‍?‍?‍?
- Ensure to talk about any questions or concerns that you or your children may have. 
- Decide whether your children will learn online or in school.

2. Email your child’s school ?
- Ask about the new policies and procedures that are in place for the reopening of schools for the 2020-2021 school year

3. Create a designated learning space ?
- If you choose to homeschool your child, ensure your child has a laptop, tablet, pencils, erasers, notebooks, binders, etc.

4. Create a schedule or routine ?
- This will help your child to gain confidence and foster independence.

5. Connect with us on Facebook or Instagram for homeschooling tips?
- Join us online for live lessons, free resources, and our weekly table talk.
 
DM for any further questions!

node.text:
Research engineers at MIT and Brigham Women’s Hospital have designed a prototype for a mask that can be reused. This mask is a silicone rubber mask with an N95 filter that is just as effective at stopping viral particles when compared to a normal N95 mask. These masks can be easily sterilized multiple times which allows for reuse. There is still an urgent need for N95 masks in hospitals across the world and especially in the United States due to the coronavirus pandemic. The engineers are using feedback from healthcare workers to create a second versioning of the mask. They are currently looking for a company to scale up production and to seek approval from the FDA and the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health. (@brandon.mathew_ )

Image may contain: night, text that says 'have been waking up. When it's still dark and I am still tired. Awake before be. want to One night, In the beginning, jettisoned out of sleep. On my feet, frantic. threw up light switches, and flug up windows. Is this hyperventilating? thought as panted and panicked. Other nights woke up slowly. Trudging through an unquiet forest of tense, tangled dreams, my heavy eyes would open. Looking for light.'.

Photo by Blue Violetta on August 19, 2020. Image may contain: night, text that says 'I started sleeping with a shade open. needed to see an open sky that was not falling. needed to see a bright, shining moon. One night, Through the open shade, The silhouetted trees in our yard shuddered and shook in the spring wind. The clouds were smeared across the predawn like icy, city slush. Grey, turbulent... moonless. Why is this pandemic happening? No longer scared. angry. was'.

Photo by Blue Violetta on August 19, 2020. Image may contain: night, text that says 'All that was worked for. All that was planned. All that was envisioned and intended. All that was imagined, conceptualized and conceived. All the hopes for this year. Gone and replaced with this? Novel, never imagined stressors. Humid hands in rubber gloves. Itchy faces in masks. Contaminated groceries. Baffling lesson plans. Children forced into remoteness. Adults forced into hardship. All the unknowns.'.

Photo by Blue Violetta on August 19, 2020. Image may contain: night, text that says 'What dreary, despondent life lies ahead now? Unvisited cities full of empty streets? Traumatized, phobic, far apart people? Global yearning For live music, live voices and social closeness? How will we let go of fear if we live in it for longer and longer? What are we supposed to learn from this? And you.. Where are you in this pandemic? No longer questioning. wanted answers.'.

Photo by Blue Violetta on August 19, 2020. Image may contain: night, text that says 'looked out my open shade. A forceful wind started to bring broken clouds. Rocky outlined apertures appeared. Deep inside an opening.. there was a moon. Far behind the fast flying clouds that moved like a news crawler. There was a moon. Sometimes concealed but still there. Shining, solid and strong. will "Where am I? I am exactly where always be. In the hearts of those who do my work. In the hearts of those who turn to me. know that you are struggling with fear. But look for me and I will appear."'.

Photo by Blue Violetta on August 19, 2020. Image may contain: night, text that says 'remembered God. remembered that have to help myself. As for the future, no one can know. The unanswerable will keep me sleepless and stressed. For now, will try to get through each day. With kindness, patience and generosity. For myself. For others. am meant to learn many lessons from this. will note each one. I will help those who seem to be learning nothing.'.

Photo by Blue Violetta on August 19, 2020. Image may contain: night, text that says 'As for my dreams, I will hang on to them. I need them now more than ever. will not consider them derailed. Resentment will cause me to lose sight of them. I will keep looking for the moon if wake up. will sleep as deeply as I can while it shines on me. will not deny that it is there. The whole world is looking toward it with me.'.

node.text:
Been slowly increasing my movement. I'm pretty sensitive to heat and can't go for walks in 80° weather or above. Plus with the #pandemic, my anxiety is so palpable I find it hard to leave the house without having a full blown #panicattack. But those mornings I wake up before it gets too hot I make it a point to walk, and use my @fitbit to track my progress. I slowly increase my step goal to reflect my baseline. If I've increased my steps by almost a thousand then I increase my step goal by a thousand. I don't always have the motivation. I try to push myself to go just a little further. If Nick can lose 100 lbs in a year just by taking walks I should start to feel better if I make it a habit. Then maybe I'll feel good about taking on a job that requires physical labor. 

#fibromyalgia #movemore #vitamind #gethealthy #selfcare #mentalillness #recovery

I feel relatively confident saying that my colleagues and I in medicine have been in overdrive this year. It's always busy, but 2020 has often felt like the Twilight Zone. I am of course thankful to have a job, as millions of others have not been so lucky this year. But, I admit it: I'm burned out. ⁣1 in 3 physicians is statistically experiencing burnout at any given time! That’s a LOT. 
.⁣
I decided to add on work days during my "vacation" last month, still conducted a full telehalth clinic from my basement while quarantining 3 months ago, and have up to 150 patient results/call-backs/staff messages to get back to, among many other things! ⁣
.⁣
I took time off this week, and my goodness did I need it. I got to take my son to the park in the middle of the afternoon, and take him for ice cream; I haven't seen him this excited in a while. I feel like a new person. ⁣
.⁣
Self-care is so crucial. I can only be a good physician, mother, and wife if I take that time for myself to recharge. For those who have been in overdrive the last several months, give yourself that time; you, your family, and your work will value your recharged and happier self so much more.⁣ 
.⁣

node.text: @camels_are_mammals it’s sure better than the original estimates of 3% people getting it and dying.

@theairguitarguy Much better, for sure! The initial estimates of 3 to 5% were based on what was known at the time. No one knew how many people actually had it (no random tests for people without obvious symptoms), so the death rate was based on the cases that showed up to hospital and were quite sick. 99.7% survival sounds good, until you realise that's 75 000 Australians who would die if everyone caught it. Mostly the old and sick, true, but still...

@camels_are_mammals that’s a gross over estimate and based on a “do absolutely nothing” approach. Which is absurd. Not sure why you’d advocate to do absolutely nothing, when a few smart changes can and are being made. not to mention there are some treatments available. 

I don’t have tile to go back and forth on this one, but can send you some links to documentaries if you want to be enlightened.

I suppose it's true enough, as long as long as it's understood that "small percentage of people who do develop covid-19" is something that will only stay true as long as we take measures to keep it that way, and "complete recovery " assumes that the initial hints of long term damage to some people turn out to be false.

@melaniehobers I've seen "kills only 0.03%", and that would match "99.97% survival", but I'm not sure where the numbers came from. A simple calculation with the Australian numbers I just saw (450 deaths, 23 993 cases) gives about 1.8% of people dying. Both those numbers can be debated, but there's  a big difference from "99.97% survival"
99.97% is the last stat I saw ??

@melaniehobers The CDC shows 171 000 deaths in the US from 5 460 000 cases. Divide deaths by cases to get 0.03. That's 3%. That is unlikely to be the real % of people who would die, because of doubt in the numbers. It has taken a few years to work out "real" death rates in previous epidemics. Just a thought about our different figures - the fact that mine is 100 times larger than yours suggests that whoever calculated your rate forgot to multiply by 100 after the division (to change the decimal into a percentage)
@camels_are_mammals that’s what I just saw on a post from the CDC - I’ll try find it and tag you. The percentage after all their calculations said 99.96%
And I just saw 99.96% survival in the US (updated from the CDC website) - yeah but we need a vaccine for this one hey ?

@melaniehobers The CDC shows 171 000 deaths in the US from 5 460 000 cases. Divide deaths by cases to get 0.03. That's 3%. That is unlikely to be the real % of people who would die, because of doubt in the numbers. It has taken a few years to work out "real" death rates in previous epidemics. Just a thought about our different figures - the fact that mine is 100 times larger than yours suggests that whoever calculated your rate forgot to multiply by 100 after the division (to change the decimal into a percentage)
@camels_are_mammals that’s what I just saw on a post from the CDC - I’ll try find it and tag you. The percentage after all their calculations said 99.96%

Actually, I think it’s over 99% chance of recovery in most places.

I’m constantly thinking about my sons education and what more we can be doing to make up for the fact that given our worlds climate, his schooling will obviously not be the same. -school part time in class

node.text:
Politics slows flow of US virus funds to local public health

As the novel coronavirus began to spread through Minneapolis this spring, Health Commissioner Gretchen Musicant tore up her budget to find funds to combat the crisis. Money for test kits. Money to administer tests. Money to hire contact tracers. And yet even more money for a service that helps tracers communicate with residents in dozens of languages. While Musicant diverted workers from violence prevention and other core programs to the COVID-19 response, state officials debated how to distribute $1.87 billion Minnesota received in federal aid. As she waited, the Minnesota Zoo got $6 million in federal money to continue operations, and a debt collection company outside Minneapolis received at least $5 million from the federal Paycheck Protection Program, according to federal data.

node.text:
Com as limitações impostas pelo isolamento social, a leitura acabou tornando-se uma forte aliada dos chamados 'quarenteners'.

 "Esse momento de quarentena mostrou para as pessoas como é importante a gente aprender a estar consigo mesmo", afirma Pedro Pacífico, advogado de 27 anos, que mergulhou no mundo dos influenciadores digitais em 2017 ao criar o perfil @book.ster no Instagram. 

Ao longos dos últimos cinco meses, desde que a pandemia foi decretada pela Organização Mundial da Saúde, Pedro tem visto um grande crescimento em seu perfil literário na rede social, que agora já conta com mais de 260 mil seguidores. 

"A leitura é uma forma de você ter um momento para você. As pessoas estão tentando desenvolver hábitos mais saudáveis e a leitura é um deles. Isso talvez seja um efeito positivo do momento tão horrível que estamos vivendo", reflete. 

Quem acompanha as várias leituras que ele compartilha no Instagram todos os dias, nem imagina que esse hábito demorou para ser aprimorado. "Eu sempre gostei de ler desde criança, mas nunca fui um leitor tão assíduo. 

Eu ficava perdido na hora de escolher o livro, não sabia muito o que ler, não tinha referências". O depoimento de Pedro pode ser a realidade de muitas outras pessoas, que também se perdem na infinidade de possibilidades de leituras. 

"Eu acabava recorrendo sempre às listas de mais vendidos, achando que lá estariam os melhores livros", completa.

Quando descobriu a existência dos perfis literários na internet, passou a ser influenciado por eles, tanto a expandir o hábito da leitura, quanto a diversificá-la. "Comecei a ler livros clássicos, que eu tinha preconceito ou medo porque achava que seriam difíceis. 

Link na bio.

Fonte: Estadão

node.text: One of the themes of my coverage during the COVID-19 crisis has been a focus on workers—too much of regular food journalism is overhead shots of plates and celebrity chefs, and far too little is about the people that make all of it possible. They’re in trouble! I went back to Corona, Queens many times over a two week period, talking to a lot of the same workers from the fanciest restaurants in the city, and many of them are undocumented and haven’t earned a dollar since March. Restaurants are operating with outdoor seating only don’t have the jobs to bring them back. They rely on a patchwork array of social services, pantries, and @wckitchen distributions to even be able to eat. And an even bigger threat looms on the horizon: evictions. Go through to ny.eater.com @eater_ny for the whole story.

node.text:
WHAT HAVE YOU DONE DURING THE PANDEMIC? ??
.
I’ve personally found this to be the busiest & most productive time of my life. I’ve done so many new things that I never dreamed were possible like creating my first online course: The Blogger Blueprint & first eBook: The Pitch Playbook, hiring a business coach, visiting my family for 3 weeks, getting my real estate license...
.
I’m not saying this to brag, I’m saying this to show you that in “uncertain times” not everything has to be doom & gloom. You can create the life you want for yourself no matter what’s going on around you. You can either see things as an opportunity or a misfortune.
.
So for those who have seen this time as an opportunity, what have you done? I want to hear about your achievements below! ????

node.text:
A LETTER FROM MOTHER EARTH

"Our future depends on what you do next.”

- Mother Earth

Proud to release a passion project that comes from the heart.  This is Mother Earth’s point of view on the pandemic and her advice for the Human Race in the future. (Video in next post)

This film also marks the official launch of the @radhumanproject , which more than just a new film series.  Our mission is to build a global community of people who care about our planet, our people and our future. 

Focusing on environmental, sustainability, humanitarian and social issues, we use short films, powerful human storytelling and social impact expeditions to bring attention to the the people and organizations fighting for causes that need our attention now.

Head to the website (link in description) to learn more and to JOIN THE MOVEMENT!!!

node.text:
The more I looked into 2020 baseball, the more fascinated and concerned I became. I can’t think of a better sum of denial than adults playing to empty stadiums of card board cut outs and recorded cheering. I know they’re looking for normalcy, but why not lean into the surrealness of the pandemic? Isn’t is weirder to play to recorded cheers and photos of fans than to nothing? Instead of accepting reality as it is, they’ve created this stranger alternative.

I do think Japan’s route of filling the seats with stuffed animals is pretty endearing, though, and honestly the most genuine, since it calls back to childhood, when our stuffies were our most attentive audience and available company. 

Meanwhile, South Korea was accused of filling seats with sex dolls, which is just a great episode of the human sitcom. What do humans do when they’re forced to quarantine? Take their sex dolls to baseball games, of course! 

But by far the most disconcerting is the first image. Robots, I believe, also from South Korea, who can do the wave with signs and have SCREENS FOR FACES that you can upload your photo to during a game. Gone are the days where we have to hold our screens in front of our faces! Now our screens ARE our faces! Fuck this. 

I’m not much for memes but felt inspired by this particular subject to express it in this way. All of these memes are very @floatuniverse inspired.

node.text:
Hey everyone!
Hope your August has been going well ?
•
I'm currently halfway done with #babystep2 and honestly am getting burned out ? it's so close but so far away! ? I just want to wake up tomorrow and be: "oh hey I'm actually DEBT FREE!"
• 
I'm truly realizing the #fulltimejob I have right now feels more draining than enjoyable and am considering just doing away with it all in all (obviously not without a #backupplan ) so the job search begins again! ? the #thirdjob didn't fall through because #job1 has an issue with me having two (or more) jobs and is asking me to quit one or step down. 
•
I'll be moving so my expenses will be changing and rent will be increasing by $200 ? but I decided it was a change I needed so I can further grow as a person even in the midst of this #pandemic honestly it's been a super scary thing but I have to take the jump or I know I'll never heal
• 
Been thinking I also want to go back to school for to be an ultrasound technician. I can dip my toe into the #nursingfield without losing my mind to all the blood ?? and see if I enjoy it
•
I also started dreaming about my future plans and everything. I want to take part in the #Americorps at some point and I also want to do #SAS ( #semesteratsea ) and just take a #trainroadtrip across the U.S. but obviously getting out of debt would be my #firststep and #priority aside from my mom's health. They all seemed close but now they seem so far away from my reach  again ?? idk I've been feeling down in the dump about everything maybe the #overthinker in me is taking over ? I'm not too sure. I've been spending more than I should due to this sadness, but I have to re-check myself and get back on track with my plans ?
•
All that aside,  how have you all been doing? Mentally, emotionally, physically? 
What have your goals been? I'd love to chat more with you guys about anything and everything ? 
•

node.text:
A still from Turbulence,  @_tejucole's contribution to this week's special edition of CC: World. Floods, intensive care units, fallen statues: the compelling video collage shows a world in turmoil addressing the current situation and is inspired by the paradox and rhythm of Bruegel's paintings.

Watch the video at: 
ccworld.hkw.de

"The amount of particulate matter suspended in a given body of water is indicative of its turbidity. Incident light is scattered to a greater degree under highly turbid conditions. In any troubled body of water, some sediments will eventually settle of their own accord. Other particles, in colloidal form, will remain suspended. In such cases, mechanical or chemical intervention is required to reduce the haziness of the water.

The appeal of Bruegel’s paintings in a time like this has something to do with the paradox they contain. Paintings don’t move. They are soundless. Bruegel’s paintings are rhythmic in composition and often unconcerned with world events. But they take place in a world of concerns, in a loud and agitated world. Hunters in the Snow was completed in 1565, The Blind Leading the Blind in 1568, and during these years, the Spanish Netherlands is falling violently apart.

Turbulence was made in conversation with and in part addressed to, among others, Love is the Message, the Message is Death by Arthur Jafa, Stopover in Dubai and Sans Soleil by Chris Marker, The Mirror and Solaris by Tarkovsky, Meshes of the Afternoon by Maya Deren and Alexander Hamid, Best of Luck with the Wall and Concussion Protocol by Josh Begley, Powaqqatsi by Godfrey Reggio, Fly Paper by Kahlil Joseph, Videograms of a Revolution by Harun Farocki, Floh by Tacita Dean, Coming Through Slaughter by Michael Ondaatje, The Rings of Saturn by W.G. Sebald, In Defense of the Poor Image by Hito Steyerl, Black and Blur by Fred Moten, and Citizen by Claudia Rankine."

— Teju Cole

node.text:
Change is an inevitable part of life that we must face. Right now is a great example of change we are being forced to go through whether we want to or not. But when it comes to change in our personal lives, this is where we can often get stuck in the familiar or comfortable. Familiar or comfortable does not mean healthy. Sometimes being uncomfortable is exactly where you need to be. In the wise words of a courageous legend, “Turn and face the strange”. David Bowie was all about change and adaptation and living in the uncomfortable. If you can tolerate it, you learn your strength and your resilience so blast some Bowie, step out of your comfort zone, and embrace the strange and the change.

node.text:
As school is starting, I can’t be the only mom who’s been a bit frazzled, trying to manage schedules, volume levels (Hubs is a public educator), food inventory, and ....I think I’ve given up on a clean house.
.
When the first wave hit in March, my beverage of choice was red wine. ?The world had gone crazy, and I was stressed. ?Who had the motivation to “think healthy thoughts”? ((Even though I was secretly hoping the motivation would just appear out of nowhere—my mindset was a mess.))
.
Fast forward to today: I’ve swapped the wine for coffee, green tea, or water with lime/lemon. (Shocker, right?)

Here were 3 things I did to make sure I stayed motivated (once I finally got fed up with being over-stressed & destroying myself with unhealthy habits):

1.) I wrote down things I thought might get in my way. “I don’t have time,” “I don’t have the energy,” “I don’t have the workout space...”
.
2.) I put myself in the role of a friend listening to me, and came up with possible solutions for how to get around everything I listed in step 1. 
 * Everybody has 30 minutes.
 * When were the slots in my day when I was available and most likely to stick to my appointment with myself? 
 * Space:  I chose my bedroom where I would have the most privacy and quiet.  We have a Firestick, and I stream my workouts. This space became my sanctuary. 

3. ). I adjusted my physical environment and communicated to the rest of my household what changes I was making.

* I put my weights and workout clothes within easy reach of my workout space.

* I tossed junk food, asked Hubs not to buy wine, and planned our meals for the week (my coach helped me with that).

* I also started on my inner transformation.  I knew that if I was going to stick with this, I had to find a way to stay mentally connected to it.  I was really lacking in the positivity department.  I had burned out, and hadn’t realized it.  So I started with the nearest positivity book I had.  10 minutes a day was what I started with.

I get asked sometimes if I ever miss how things were (my wine at night). 

Not really. ?? I manage my stress differently these days.  Helpful?  Let me know!  Comment ??

As the #world grapples with the #coronavirus pandemic, humans everywhere face #unemployment, pay cuts, and even #homelessness, but one specific group continues to thrive... the ‘Oligarchic Dozen.’⁣
⁣
New research by the #US’ Institute for Policy Studies (#IPS) found the top 12 #American billionaires have seen their combined #wealth soar by 40 percent, or $283 billion, to over $1 trillion since the health #crisis began. The new total is more than the #GDP of #Belgium and #Austria combined, and marks the first time it has hit the #trillion mark.⁣
⁣
Jeff Bezos, Bill Gates, Mark Zuckerberg, Warren Buffett, and Elon Musk make up the top five of the #billionaire boys’ club. Following them is Steve Ballmer, Larry Ellison, Larry Page, Sergey Brin, Alice Walton, Jim Walton, and Rob Walton. Between January and March, their collective wealth dipped by $96 billion. But the dent turned out to be inconsequential when the #billions suddenly rebounded, surpassing their September 2019 #Forbes 400 wealth level.⁣
⁣
According to the report, little old Warren Buffett was the only exception: he’s still $2 billion below his September 2019 wealth, meaning he’s worth only $80 billion. He's probably wiping away the tears with $100 bills right now! #Bezos and #Zuckerberg are the biggest #pandemic success stories so far, with the #Amazon CEO increasing his wealth by $76 billion (68 percent) to $189.4 billion, and the #Facebook CEO by $40.8 billion (75 percent) to $95.5 billion. So, the pandemic really has been the #best of times, and the #worst of times...⁣
⁣
The report claims, ‘This is a disturbing milestone in the US history of concentrated wealth and power. This is simply too much economic and political power in the hands of 12 people. From the point of view of a democratic self-governing society, this represents an Oligarchic Twelve or a Despotic Dozen.’

node.text: Us too ??? Being a teacher it’s like a double edged sword...worrying about my students and balancing taking care of my own- which is priority?! ? I am thinking of you....and all the parents out there. Find the joy and remember the “before” and what we are missing out on...which is a lot ?

I feel you, friend. Our school district gave us 5 days for all parents to decide to distance learning or go in person. I signed my oldest up for distance learning because I know he’ll struggle to keep a mask on. I ran out of time deciding what to do with our kindergartener. Now she’s going in person, and I’m wishing it was the other way around because my son has an IEP. It’s such a confusing mess and I’m longing for the day this is all just a bad memory. Hugs to you and your boys as you navigate new and uncomfortable waters together ??

Us too ??? Being a teacher it’s like a double edged sword...worrying about my students and balancing taking care of my own- which is priority?! ? I am thinking of you....and all the parents out there. Find the joy and remember the “before” and what we are missing out on...which is a lot ?

I feel you, friend. Our school district gave us 5 days for all parents to decide to distance learning or go in person. I signed my oldest up for distance learning because I know he’ll struggle to keep a mask on. I ran out of time deciding what to do with our kindergartener. Now she’s going in person, and I’m wishing it was the other way around because my son has an IEP. It’s such a confusing mess and I’m longing for the day this is all just a bad memory. Hugs to you and your boys as you navigate new and uncomfortable waters together ??

It’s a hard week over here. Too much time indoors looking at screens has made us short with one another. We’re all mourning the fact that “school” isn’t the same this year- the oldest has been so sad that he should be in class with his friends & a teacher he loves, already a third grader. We’re all dreading looking at computers & trying to figure out all the assignments together. At home. We all deeply feel the loss of our communities, of friends. Of time spent with other people. We’re sad. And tired. And stuck.

We have so much to be thankful for, & we are! But this week we’re thankful AND sad. Doing fine and struggling. Trying to embrace this season and anxiously awaiting life after a pandemic.

If you’re living in a lot of “and” right now know you’re not alone. ? Things are far from perfect and it’s okay. Better days are coming ??

We are proud to partner with The Coalition for Behavioral Health on the Frontline Essential Workers (FEW) Hotline! The FEW Line is free, confidential and available to all NYC community-based providers and essential workers in emotional distress, Monday through Friday, 10am-10pm. Call 866-565-7715 to be connected with a trained, caring counselor.

Learn more about the FEW Line at the link in the @vibrantforall Instagram bio!

node.text:
Announcing the cabinet’s approval of a 30% cut in the salaries of the President, Vice-President, Prime Minister, Governors, and MPs, Information and Broadcasting Minister Prakash Javdekar said, "President, Vice President, Governors voluntarily decided to take a pay cut.”
He also added that the cabinet approved reduction in allowances, pension of MPs by 30% for a year to fight COVID-19. 
“This is a landmark decision that sends the right signals," Javedkar told reporters.
The government says the salary cut will be applicable for a year. Pension and allowances of MPs however will remain unaffected. The saved money will go to the Consolidated Fund of India.

APA HARI TERBAIKMU?

Saudaraku...
Apa hari terbaik bagimu..?
Dulukah..?
Kemarin..?
Atau saat ini..?
Apa hari terbaik menurutmu..?

Apakah pada saat itu engkau mendapatkan hadiah yang engkau idam-idamkan..?
Ataukah pada hari itu engkau mendapatkan suasana hati yang amat bergembira karena suatu hal yang engkau senangi momentnya..?
Ataukah yang lain?

Ibnul Qoyyim rahimahullah berkata:
.
??? ???? ????? ??? ??????? ? ??????? ? ??? ????? ??? ????.
.
"Hari terbaik dan utama bagi seorang hamba adalah hari dimana ia bertaubat kepada Allah." (Zadul Ma'ad, 3/512)

Ya itulah saudaraku hakekat sebenarnya hari terbaikmu..
Hari dimana engkau bisa khusyuk benar-benar menangisi dan menyesali dosa-dosa di masa lalu, engkau lakukan Itu dengan bersimpuh memohon rahmat dan ampunanNya. Maka itulah hari terbaik bagimu..

Semoga Allah memberikan taufiq kepada kita untuk selalu bertaubat dan senantiasa kembali kepada-Nya..

As coronavirus ?spreads throughout the US??, dental practices across the country are seeing big challenges because of the virus.

Tip 4 getting out of the COVID maze: Let’s dive into specials. Below is a tick list for follow up systems.

-	Offer a New Patient Special and promote on social media in your specific area with your preferred demographics. You should also print your social media ad and give it to your patient to let them know you are offering a great special if they were thinking of referring a friend or family member.  Print direct marketing is a nice addition to this strategy. 

-	Have a quick and easy special like teeth whitening for example. Promote on social media in your specific area with your preferred demographics which ideally would be your current patient base and new patients.

-	Blast your special via appointment reminder systems or mass email system.

node.text:
WWE is moving the the Amway Center and the ThunderDome might not be the only thing with a lot of possibilities. A new rumor bubbling within WWE could point to some big returns as well.

The company will still be testing for COVID-19 prior to each taping. We’ll have to see if they have any hold-ups as those tests will now be weekly. Wrestling News says that some interesting speculation is coming from within the backstage area.

Brock Lesnar is on a hiatus, and Roman Reigns is on full quarantine. It might be possible to pull both of those names back for this new environment.

“There is now speculation amongst some people in the company that now that they are running shows at the amway centre that this will open the door for names like Brock Lesnar and Roman Reigns to return.”

Getting Roman Reigns and Brock Lesnar back on television could be a huge boost for both WWE brands. This is just speculation at the moment as we have heard of no definite plans in motion.

We’ll have to see what is in store for fans as WWE tries their best to pull the viewership up. Vince McMahon is apparently optimistic, but this is certainly the beginning of a new era in WWE’s pandemic programming. #wwe #wweraw #wwesmackdown #wwethunderdome #florida #orlando #thunderdome #return #brocklesnar #romanreigns  #virualfans #fans #wweonfox #vincemcmahon #fox #amwaycenter #prowrestling #covid19 #pandemic #bigreturn #summerslam #ehowb ??

Image may contain: text that says 'You know when you take your child doctor and they ask you how much screen time your child has per day because too much screentime is harmful developing brain. But due to COVID-19... a School Districts choosing "virtual learning" are encouragingparents to triple amount screen time recommended by American Academy of Pediatrics. #guntereverafterblog'.

node.text:
? Screen Time ?

+ I must get a half a dozen emails, text message or DM's a day about little ones becoming frustrated, upset and overwhelmed with virtual learning. And as I am thinking of solutions for those who write me I keep coming back to screentime. 

+ There is a reason why doctors tell us parents to limit screen time and this is exactly why. Children are not meant to learn online on a computer for hours at a time. If you see your child getting angry, frustrated or even anxious while online learning, go ahead an excuse them from the class for a few minutes to help them calm down. This is especially important for special needs students with disabilities like ADHD, Autism, ODD, Anxiety and other like disorders. 

+ Before anyone gets upset about the statement above let me remind you these are unprecedented times, and all these students learning virtually are in the same waters trying to learn as much as they can in a system they are not accustomed too. So if a student needs a break let them take their break.

+ We chose to homeschool ahead of the chaos of COVID-19, and we will not be sending our littles back to public schools. Through this whole homeschooling journey we learned from our babies they learn better at home in a comfortable setting where they can thrive at their own pace.

+ If you are one of the parents who have messaged me or you want to message me to discuss this topic, please do I love to help coming up with solutions to learninf problems!!!So if virtual learning is not working for you maybe it's time to try something else?

She has earned an award-winning reputation for developing technically superior skincare products. Cara’s notable brainchildren include Tata Harper Skincare’s top-ranked Resurfacing Serum, Creme Riche, and Clarifying Mask. She most recently created the best-selling The Bloomi Arousal Oil made from organic aphrodisiacs.

Cara earned her masters of science in molecular medicine and her masters of public health in epidemiology & biostatistics.

node.text:
Repost from @katiecouric
•
#FacesOfCOVID: April Dunn was born with fetal alcohol syndrome and cerebral palsy. She was a model high school student - she made the honor roll every term, participated in Junior ROTC, and never missed a day of school. But she couldn’t pass the standardized tests that were required for graduation - and therefore didn’t receive a diploma from Glen Oaks High School in Baton Rouge, Louisiana. 

Nearly a decade later, after struggling for years to find fulfilling work, April became the driving force behind a state bill to provide alternative graduation paths for students with disabilities. Along with a group of advocates, she worked tirelessly - testifying in committees and meeting with legislators - explaining how being denied a diploma made her feel undervalued and shut her out of jobs and opportunities for which she was qualified. The bill, Act 833 passed unanimously in both chambers in 2014 and helped April land a job in the administration of Gov. John Bel Edwards. She was a highly respected presence in the state capitol, unafraid to call officials at all hours of the day to discuss her efforts. “She brightened everyone’s day with her smile, was a tremendous asset to our team and an inspiration to everyone who met her,” Gov. Edwards said in a statement.

April fell ill with COVID-like symptoms in mid-March after returning from a work trip where she was helping people in southern Louisiana advocate for accessible and affordable housing. She tested positive for COVID-19 and died in a hospital on March 28. She was 33 years old. 

Her death highlights COVID-19’s merciless impact on people with disabilities and underlying health problems - who face vastly greater risks of hospitalization and fatal infection than the rest of the population. April was well aware of the dangers — in her last Facebook post, shared shortly after she developed symptoms, she uploaded a picture of herself and some friends with the caption “Only the vulnerable will be at risk. Your ‘only’ is my everything.” Rest In Peace, April. You mattered.
#covid19 #staysafe #pandemic #prayers #photooftheday #picoftheday #photo #beautiful #love #wednesdaymotivation #louisiana

? I want you to see what you inspired me to do, one day.

I LOVE THIS PICTURE! It reminds me of God’s Grace while living through a Pandemic. It reminds of the restful quarantine time. It reminds me of how far I’ve come. With cotton peeking over my shoulder it reminds me that I am a OVERCOMER. Once having family that picked cotton for free to OWNING land and fields. 
—————————————
Prospering in a Pandemic 
There are so many people who are prospering in a pandemic. Not just in their finances but in wellbeing, in their physical body and in their mental wellness. Everyday we wake up with more and more uncertainty yet each day I’m reminded of the goodness and grace that has gone before me. This is what allows a feeling of prosperity and gratitude. 

————————————
Perspective is Everything 

I have noticed more rainbows, watched more sunsets, caught beautiful skies of wonder and basked in the sun or danced in the rain. I realize that perspective is all that we have and when we look at things the right way, we can find something good in it.
————————————-
How are you prospering in a pandemic?

ARTE N.36 - ENTRE 4 PAREDES – DAYS – 2020 – FINE ART – 67,5 X 90 cm

Life in reconstruction. Em descoberta. Em recriac?a?o. LIFE... LIFE... LIFE... Uma solitude de espac?os compartilhados, buscados, perseguidos e reaprendidos no cotidiano. Um sossegar de dia enquanto a luz da tarde vai, aos poucos, iluminando a sala, desanuviando as incertezas e aquecendo a pele. Uma pandemia a assistir as histo?rias que se apresentam, se reconhecem, entrelac?am e consolidam. LIFE... LIFE... VIDA... Life with her is better! Says who? Life with him is better! Every Day? Life together is amazing! What else do you want. Os dias seguem e vamos aprendendo a ressignificar o tempo, perpetrando novas atitudes e sentimentos. O sile?ncio vai sendo preenchido pelos pensamentos, histo?rias, planos e amanheceres. LIFE... LIVES... VIVER... Reaquecer a mente e a boca com palavras, emoc?o?es, olhares e certezas. Today...2 Days... Days... A Week... Weeks... Monday to Sunday... Em meio aos meses que foram solidificando as histo?rias, fundindo olhares e propondo novas jornadas, o amor vai se percebendo so?lido companheiro, se preenchendo de lar, de presenc?a, de vida a dois. Tell me! Say it! No brincar com as palavras, com os significados e as li?nguas, o DIA e o DIZ seguem pelas semanas e meses. Day and Says seguindo cadenciados, na mesma batida, freque?ncia e sintonia. 
Arte Digital criada a partir do esti?mulo fotogra?fico do casal de atores Day Mesquita @daymesquita1 e Pedro Says @pedrosays1  durante o isolamento social.

node.text:
Out of all of the different ways I imagined Amelia's first day of Kindergarten, I never could have imagined this. Her first day consisted of a scheduled book pick up, with her mask, so she could meet her teacher in person and see what her classroom will look like when she, eventually, goes to school ? 
She was nervous, and truthfully so was I! Her and I sat in the car for a minute before walking in, and talked through the all of the different feelings. We were both so excited for her to start school, but we were also nervous because this is something new. We love that she gets to spend the time at home with us, but we're also overwhelmed because that is a LOT of time at home. We are pumped about her curriculum and the amount she is going to be learning by time this year is over... But we also feel like deer in the head lights because neither one of us know how we are going to get this all done, on our own, while I'm on bedrest, with Evie present, during a pandemic ?
In short, we're excited, but we have no idea what we're doing ? So, together, we are going to take this this one small step at a time; while learning every step of the way, and making a million mistakes ? 
.
.

Tonight at 6, join Lino Kino members Emilie Slater and Michael Ipsen in a live conversation and public Q&A with video artist Boothe Carlson to discuss her work, ??????????, which premiered this week on icaphila.org as part of Open Video Call 2020.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Wednesday, August 19⁣⁣
6–7PM⁣⁣
Live captioning will be provided.⁣
⁣
For details on how to join the conversation, click the link in our profile⁣.
⁣
?????????? is the fourth of eight works premiering weekly as part of Open Video Call, an annual screening of curated videos by Philadelphia-area artists, curated this year by local media arts collective Lino Kino (@linokinovideo). To view the full work, along with this year's past premieres, visit icaphila.org, or click the link in our profile.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
About the artist:⁣⁣
Boothe Carlson makes videos, and occasionally music, though during COVID19 she is spending as much time as possible in direct sunlight. As a child she enjoyed sitting in the car while her dad drove her forty-five minutes to softball practice. Originally from Berkeley, California, she now lives in Philadelphia but fantasizes about moving to New Mexico.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
About the work:⁣⁣
??????????’s playful humor introduces some much-needed nuance to the dialogue around the current crisis, neither disparaging these new safety measures, nor being wholly deferential to them, but rather existing somewhere in between. Carlson recognizes the value of masks and social distancing, while acknowledging the mental whiplash caused by the quantum shift in our understanding of what is normal.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Image: Boothe Carlson, ??????????, 2020. Video (color, sound), 01:21 min.⁣⁣

node.text:
Alhamdulillah 'ala kulli haal, setiap bencana apa pun yang menimpa seorang Muslim hikmahnya adalah  digugurkannya dosa-dosa. Hadist dan Riwayatnya sudah mutafaqun 'alaih. 

Banyak orang di luar sana menganggap skizofrenia @peduliskizofrenia adalah gangguan kesehatan mental yang sangat keras. Padahal faktanya tidak seperti itu, hal itu hanya ada di Psikopat dan Psikopatologis, seorang penyintas skizofrenia: adalah yang berada di dalam kondisi alam bawah sadarnya (deepest mind) adalah kenangan buruk, kenangan pahit, penghakiman manusia, penolakan dari lingkungan sekitar, bullying, label depresif mayor, kalimat-kalimat tajam/intervensif dan bentakan dari penolakan orang lain di lingkungan sekitarnya yang membuat diri lembutnya menjadi sangat rapuh dan menjadi tantrum. Bahkan bisa jadi faktor pemicunya justru dari hal-hal sangat kecil yang disuarakan dengan nada membentak-bentak seperti Toxic People dan Toxic Masculinity dan membuat kepalanya sangat pusing, perutnya mual, berat badannya turun drastis, dan sering muntah di wastafel melihat penolakan di lingkungan sekitarnya, dari Tsunami Selat Sunda 2018 lalu, sampai sekarang saat ini aku mengalami kenangan traumatis di dunia psikiatris disebut dengan Post Traumatic Stress Disorder di mana seseorang bisa sangat takut untuk masuk ke ruangan seseorang yang menolak kehadiran dirinya dan sangat takut dengan seragam atau atribut. Aku jadi teringat kalimat dokter psikiatris @jiemiardian di mana leganya seseorang itu berbeda-beda dan kita tidak perlu menghakimi dan melabeli orang lain. Pada #pandemic #covid19 ini aku sangat bersyukur kepada Allah karena ditengah-tengah #pandemic ini justru Allah hadirkan dokter-dokter luar biasa dan teman-teman luar biasa yang mensupport aku dari jauh. Sebelum jiwaku benar-benar hancur maka aku harus berdamai dengan masa lalu agar jiwaku kembali utuh dan tidak perlu mendengarkan penghakiman orang lain lagi. 

Hikmahnya dari Allah tidak pernah terduga, jalan hidupnya seorang manusia juga tidak pernah terduga, dokter aku berkata: "di dunia ini tidak ada yang kebetulan Ibu, Zaki ini sebenarnya anak yang cerdas. Pemahamannya sudah sampai Tasawuf, aku aja merinding dengar Zaki bicara, Bu."

node.text: The World Health Organization (WHO) reports that nurses, doctors, and medical professionals all over the world are united in their resolve to do everything in their power to help learn more about and mitigate COVID-19. Nurses are reorganizing wards to open more beds for COVID-19 patients, while keeping others, including women in labor, safe. They’re taking stock of equipment and lending it across units. Healthcare workers are learning on the job with information that changes daily – even hourly. Some medical professionals are preparing educational videos and teaching colleagues to optimize their PPE. Overall, the super nurses and other medical workers are working tirelessly to keep us all safe and healthy!

Need to run out and do errands with the kids in tow? It will help kids feel more confident and manage their behavior if you emphasize that reopening is a gradual process, one careful step after another. That may mean establishing rules about maintaining that six-foot distance from their people and keeping their mask on. You can also discuss what other steps might come down the road, so that kids know you’re planning ahead even if they can’t do everything they want just yet.

BREAKING NEWS 
Pharmacists Vaccine Authority During the Pandemic
:
:
:
? Pharmacists in all 50 states are now allowed to give childhood vaccinations under a new directive aimed at preventing future outbreaks of measles and other preventable diseases.

? Alex Azar, the head of the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, took the step using emergency powers he has during the U.S. coronavirus epidemic declaring a public health emergency. 

? The directive announced TODAY will temporarily preempt restrictions in 22 states starting this fall.

? This move is designed to help prevent vaccination rates from falling during the pandemic.

? The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention @cdcgov has reported that orders for childhood vaccines from doctors’ offices plummeted in late March and early April as their offices closed or saw fewer patients, raising concerns that vaccination rates would fall.

shortcode_media.title: Long Haulers: New Disease or Novel Expression of and Old Concept?

node.text:
As millions of people around the world are recovering from COVID-19, a small subset of this group is not getting better but staying ill. This group has been referred to in the media as “Long Haulers.” Even though this represents a small fraction of those infected with COVID-19, due to the enormity of its worldwide spreading, the absolute numbers with this new syndrome is extensive. What these individuals are experiencing is a post viral inflammatory syndrome, scientifically referred to as Post-COVID Inflammatory Syndrome (PCIS), though the official name is still in evolution.

In this short video I would like to introduce the idea of PCIS. We will briefly discuss other post inflammatory syndromes and other potential antecedents* to these diseases. We will also share our interest in the disorder and a potential future educational class in which we can dive into these topics.

*an antecedent is something that predisposes an individual to a reaction or disease. Often these are unrecognized by the individual.

Watch this video on our site: richmondfunctionalmedicine.com/social-media/long-haulers-new-disease-or-novel-expression-of-and-old-concept/

node.text: @katiefordvet ?. That is a good one. Your lessons on retraining your brain have helped me learn this. Thanks!
The power of gratitude ? I'm definitely more grateful for freedom that I took for granted before (and I'm definitely more grateful for toilet roll too it seems ?)
@dr.magda.vet I noticed the slow down too. It was nice before the clinic exploded. ?

Definitely the power of togetherness, and gratitude and enjoyment of the simple things. I actually really enjoyed our short period of lockdown, because all our external activities stopped and I had hubby home to help - it made me realise just how busy my day to day life is, and how this is not necessarily a good thing!! ?
@it.might.get.weird That makes perfect sense. I definitely realize that things will not go according to plan most days. Trying to have more gratitude for the thighs that do work out.
@it.might.get.weird ???. I guess the sentence works either way. I meant the highs.... but my thighs are not working out either.

Great post. This is hard to say, because it’s just crushing to admit to, but I’m learning to be less disappointed by disappointment. Does that make sense? I kind of expect all my plans to fall through! But on the flip side, I’m cherish even more the little things I look forward to that actually happen.
@it.might.get.weird ???. I guess the sentence works either way. I meant the highs.... but my thighs are not working out either.

Pre mask wearing and sweater weather!  Take me back to 2019. This year has been rough. I keep hearing so many say “when things get back to NORMAL”...

Unfortunately I believe this is our NEW normal for a while. Therefore we must adapt if we want to not just survive, but also thrive. 

To keep me sane I focus on these things:
- I have a job and get to continue to do what I love. #essentialworker ?‍??
- My family is healthy. 
- We have learned more about being #bettertogether since this all started. 
- The services I provide matter. So many peoples pets are one of their main sources of joy these days, and we keep them healthy. ??

What are some things you have become more aware of and grateful for during the #pandemic ?  Share them below.

Delayed test results are problematic now, but even more problematic early on, when cases were lower and we could have used efficient testing to contact trace and slow the spread of COVID. If it’s going to take up to two weeks to get test results now, then all we can do is quarantine if we’re symptomatic and assume we’re positive until we get our results back.
